# CALIBRATION EXAMPLES
Hand-graded excerpts showing what each score level means in practice.
Match this calibration. If your scoring drifts higher than these anchors, you are being generous — lower it.

## Example 1 — criterion: domain_modeling_fit, correct score: 0.3
```
// PROJECT_DATABASE.md declares: User, Application, Document,
// PaymentRequest, RefundRecord, Notice, FAQ, Company, CompanyStaff,
// ServiceType, BankAccount.

// Actual entities:
//   user.entity.ts (User with role: 'worker' | 'admin')
//   application.entity.ts
//   notice.entity.ts
//   faq.entity.ts

// Missing: Document, PaymentRequest, RefundRecord, Company,
//          CompanyStaff, ServiceType, BankAccount.
//
// Application entity has fields: documents (jsonb), payments (jsonb),
// refundInfo (jsonb) — all the missing entities folded into JSON
// columns on Application.
```
**Why this score:** Seven of eleven declared entities missing. Folded into JSON columns on Application — kills queryability, breaks audit trails, makes future migrations painful. Domain model not represented.

## Example 2 — criterion: domain_modeling_fit, correct score: 0.9
```
// All 11 declared entities exist as proper tables:
//   user.entity.ts          @Entity('users')
//   application.entity.ts   @Entity('applications')
//   document.entity.ts      @Entity('documents')
//   payment-request.entity.ts @Entity('payment_requests')
//   refund-record.entity.ts @Entity('refund_records')
//   notice.entity.ts        @Entity('notices')
//   faq.entity.ts           @Entity('faqs')
//   company.entity.ts       @Entity('companies')
//   company-staff.entity.ts @Entity('company_staff')
//   service-type.entity.ts  @Entity('service_types')
//   bank-account.entity.ts  @Entity('bank_accounts')
//
// Field names use domain vocabulary: reference_number (not "code"),
// service_type_id (not "type_id"), application_status (not "status").
// Status enum values use declared Korean keys + English mapping.
```
**Why this score:** Every declared entity present as a proper table. Domain vocabulary preserved in column names. Distinct concepts get distinct tables.

## Example 3 — criterion: relationships_correctness, correct score: 0.2
```
@Entity()
export class Application {
  @Column() user_id: string;     // FK column but no @ManyToOne
  @Column() service_type_id: string;
}

@Entity()
export class PaymentRequest {
  @Column() application_id: string;
  @ManyToOne(() => Application, { onDelete: 'CASCADE' })
  application: Application;
}
// Deleting an Application CASCADE-deletes PaymentRequests.
// PRD says: "Payment audit trail must be retained 5 years even
// if application is cancelled."
```
**Why this score:** Application has FK columns but no @ManyToOne — TypeORM won't eager-load. PaymentRequest CASCADE-deletes when Application removed, violating the explicit 5-year audit retention rule.

## Example 4 — criterion: relationships_correctness, correct score: 0.9
```
@Entity('applications')
export class Application {
  @ManyToOne(() => User, { nullable: false })
  @JoinColumn({ name: 'user_id' })
  user: User;
  @Column('uuid') user_id: string;

  @ManyToOne(() => ServiceType, { nullable: false })
  @JoinColumn({ name: 'service_type_id' })
  serviceType: ServiceType;
  @Column('uuid') service_type_id: string;
}

@Entity('payment_requests')
export class PaymentRequest {
  @ManyToOne(() => Application, { onDelete: 'RESTRICT' })
  @JoinColumn({ name: 'application_id' })
  application: Application;
  // 5-year retention required — RESTRICT prevents accidental cascade.
}
```
**Why this score:** Both relationship sides explicit. @JoinColumn names match column. RESTRICT on PaymentRequest preserves audit trail per PRD's retention rule. CASCADE used only where children have no standalone audit value.

## Example 5 — criterion: constraint_correctness, correct score: 0.3
```
@Entity('users')
export class User {
  @PrimaryGeneratedColumn('uuid') id: string;
  @Column() email: string;          // not unique
  @Column() phone: string;          // nullable, no index
  @Column() role: string;           // no index — every dashboard scans
}

@Entity('applications')
export class Application {
  @Column() reference_number: string;  // not unique — collisions possible
  @Column() status: string;            // no index — status filters scan
}
```
**Why this score:** Email not unique — duplicate accounts allowed. Reference number can collide. Status / role unindexed — every dashboard does a sequential scan. No NOT NULL on email despite being a required field per PRD.

## Example 6 — criterion: constraint_correctness, correct score: 0.9
```
@Entity('users')
@Index('idx_users_role', ['role'])
export class User {
  @Column({ unique: true, nullable: false }) email: string;
  @Column({ nullable: false }) phone: string;
  @Column({ type: 'enum', enum: UserRole, default: UserRole.WORKER })
  role: UserRole;
}

@Entity('applications')
@Index('idx_applications_status', ['status'])
@Index('idx_applications_user_status', ['user_id', 'status'])
@Unique('uq_applications_reference_number', ['reference_number'])
export class Application {
  @Column({ nullable: false }) reference_number: string;
  @Column({ type: 'enum', enum: ApplicationStatus }) status: ApplicationStatus;
}
```
**Why this score:** Email + reference_number unique. NOT NULL on required fields. Indexes on status (single-column) and (user_id, status) composite for "my applications by status" — the worker home dashboard's most common query.

## Example 7 — criterion: migration_safety, correct score: 0.2
```
// ormconfig.ts — production
synchronize: true,   // production auto-sync — data-corruption risk

// 003-add-fields.ts
await q.query(`ALTER TABLE applications ADD COLUMN priority varchar NOT NULL`);
await q.query(`DROP COLUMN applications.legacy_code`);
// Migration doesn't run successfully on populated DB:
//   - NOT NULL has no default, no backfill
//   - Legacy column dropped without grace period
```
**Why this score:** synchronize:true in production = silent schema drift / data loss. Migration would fail on any non-empty applications table. Legacy column dropped in same step that adds new — clients still using legacy_code break immediately on deploy.

## Example 8 — criterion: migration_safety, correct score: 0.9
```
// ormconfig.ts — production
synchronize: false,
migrationsRun: true,

// 003-add-priority-additive.ts
await q.query(`ALTER TABLE applications ADD COLUMN priority varchar`);  // nullable
await q.query(`UPDATE applications SET priority = 'normal' WHERE priority IS NULL`);
await q.query(`ALTER TABLE applications ALTER COLUMN priority SET NOT NULL`);
await q.query(`ALTER TABLE applications ALTER COLUMN priority SET DEFAULT 'normal'`);

// 004-deprecate-legacy-code.ts (run weeks later, after clients update)
await q.query(`ALTER TABLE applications DROP COLUMN legacy_code`);
```
**Why this score:** Forward-safe NOT NULL addition (additive → backfill → enforce). synchronize:false in production. Legacy column dropped in a separate later migration after clients have updated. Reversible if needed.

